goals.question: What is the distribution of population across zip codes?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of population across different zip codes and identify any outliers.

goals.question: What is the average income of households in each zip code?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of average income by zip code
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the zip codes with higher average income and understand the income distribution across different zip codes.

goals.question: What is the relationship between population and number of businesses in each zip code?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of population vs number of businesses
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any correlation between population and number of businesses in each zip code.

goals.question: What is the distribution of land area across zip codes?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of land area across different zip codes and identify any outliers.

goals.question: What is the racial diversity in each zip code?
goals.visualization: Stacked bar chart of racial distribution by zip code
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the racial diversity in each zip code and identify any patterns or discrepancies.

code:

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
data = pd.read_csv('zipcodes.csv')

# Plot histogram of population
sns.histplot(data=data, x='population', kde=True, color='blue')
plt.axvline(data['population'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(data['population'].median()))
plt.title('What is the distribution of population across zip codes?', wrap=True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
data = pd.read_csv('zipcodes.csv')

# Calculate average income by zip code
avg_income = data.groupby('Zip')['Income'].mean().reset_index()

# Create bar chart
sns.set_style('whitegrid')
sns.barplot(x='Zip', y='Income', data=avg_income, color='blue')

# Set chart title and axis labels
plt.title('What is the average income of households in each zip code?')
plt.xlabel('Zip Code')
plt.ylabel('Average Income')

# Show plot
plt.show()
```

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.scatterplot(x='population', y='businesses', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the relationship between population and number of businesses in each zip code?', wrap=True)
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('zipcodes.csv')
chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
data = pd.read_csv('zipcodes.csv')

# Pivot data to get racial distribution by zip code
data_pivot = data.pivot_table(index='zip_code', columns='race', values='count')

# Plot stacked bar chart
ax = sns.barplot(x=data_pivot.index, y=data_pivot['White'], color='blue')
ax = sns.barplot(x=data_pivot.index, y=data_pivot['Black'], color='orange', ax=ax)
ax = sns.barplot(x=data_pivot.index, y=data_pivot['Hispanic'], color='green', ax=ax)
ax = sns.barplot(x=data_pivot.index, y=data_pivot['Asian'], color='red', ax=ax)
ax = sns.barplot(x=data_pivot.index, y=data_pivot['Other'], color='purple', ax=ax)

# Set chart title and legend
plt.title('What is the racial diversity in each zip code?', wrap=True)
ax.legend(['White', 'Black', 'Hispanic', 'Asian', 'Other'])

# Rotate x-axis labels for legibility
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

# Return plot object
plt.show()
```
